WEBVTT

01:12.948 --> 01:14.407
Finished, sir?

01:14.491 --> 01:16.033
Yeah . Hey, do you have a light?

01:24.042 --> 01:25.209
Old Gold man , huh?

01:26.670 --> 01:28.337
Lucky Strike here.

01:30.048 --> 01:32.592
Can I ask you a question?
Why do you smoke Old Gold?

01:32.676 --> 01:34.969
I'm sorry, sir,
Is Sam here bothering you?

01:35.053 --> 01:37.722
He can be a little chatty.

01:37.806 --> 01:40.057
No, we're actually just
having a conversation .

01:40.142 --> 01:41.058
Is that okay?

01:41.143 --> 01:43.978
Can I get you another drink?

01:44.062 --> 01:47.064
Yeah. Do this again .
Old-fashioned , please.

01:49.401 --> 01:51.986
So you obviously need to relax
after working here all night.

01:52.070 --> 01:54.405
I guess. I don't know.

01:54.490 --> 01:55.990
But what is it? I mean , low-tar?

01:56.074 --> 01:56.991
Those new filters?

01:57.075 --> 01:58.451
Why-- I mean-- Why Old Gold?

01:58.535 --> 02:00.828
They gave 'em to us in the service--

02:00.913 --> 02:02.330
a carton a week for free.

02:02.414 --> 02:04.040
So you're used to 'em ,
is that it?

02:04.124 --> 02:07.001
Yeah . They're a habit.

02:07.085 --> 02:09.003
I could never get you
to try another brand--

02:09.087 --> 02:10.963
say, my Luckies?

02:11.048 --> 02:14.008
I love my Old Golds.

02:14.092 --> 02:17.887
All right, well, let's just say tomorrow
a tobacco weevil comes

02:17.971 --> 02:20.973
and eats every last
Old Gold on the planet.

02:21.058 --> 02:22.767
That's a sad story.

02:22.851 --> 02:25.645
It's a tragedy.

02:25.729 --> 02:27.104
Would you just stop smoking?

02:28.565 --> 02:30.858
I think I could find something .

02:30.943 --> 02:32.193
I love smoking .

02:32.277 --> 02:34.987
"I love smoking." That's very good .

02:35.072 --> 02:36.656
My wife hates it.

02:36.740 --> 02:38.866
Reader's Digest says it will kill you .

02:39.952 --> 02:41.118
Yeah, I heard about that.

02:42.329 --> 02:44.914
Ladies love their magazines.

02:45.999 --> 02:47.333
Yes, they do.

03:19.366 --> 03:22.076
You weren't worried
about waking me, were you?

03:22.160 --> 03:23.411
Am I interrupting anything?

03:23.495 --> 03:24.829
Mmm , no.

03:27.791 --> 03:32.712
You're lucky I'm still up working
and I'm alone.

03:32.796 --> 03:34.088
How's it going?

03:34.172 --> 03:37.925
They invented something called
Grandmother's Day.

03:38.010 --> 03:42.930
That ought to keep me busy
drawing puppies for a few months.

03:43.015 --> 03:44.932
Can I run a few ideas past you?

03:45.017 --> 03:46.851
Does that mean
what I think it means?

03:46.935 --> 03:50.021
Because I'm familiar
with most of your ideas.

03:50.105 --> 03:52.148
I'm having a situation
with my cigarette account.

03:52.232 --> 03:55.776
Wow, you really are here to talk.

03:55.861 --> 03:58.779
The Trade Commission is cracking down
on all of our health claims.

03:58.864 --> 04:00.990
I getReader's Digest.

04:01.074 --> 04:03.492
This is the same scare
you had five years ago.

04:03.577 --> 04:04.785
You dealt with it.

04:04.870 --> 04:08.164
I know I slept a lot better
knowing doctors smoke.

04:08.248 --> 04:09.206
Well, that's just it.

04:09.291 --> 04:12.501
The whole "safer cigarette"
thing is over.

04:12.586 --> 04:14.587
No more doctors,
no more testimonials,

04:14.671 --> 04:18.132
no more cough-free,
soothes your T-zone,

04:18.216 --> 04:20.176
low-tar, low-nicotine, filter tip.

04:20.260 --> 04:22.011
Nothing .

04:22.095 --> 04:24.639
All I have is a crush-proof box

04:24.723 --> 04:28.184
and "four out of five
dead people smoke your brand ."

04:28.268 --> 04:30.019
Is this the part where I say,

04:30.103 --> 04:33.147
"Don Draper is the greatest ad man ever,

04:33.231 --> 04:36.150
"and his big, strong brain will find a way

04:36.234 --> 04:38.277
to lead the sheep
to the slaughterhouse"?

04:40.113 --> 04:42.949
I don't want to go to school tomorrow.

04:43.033 --> 04:45.201
You gonna pitch to me or not?

04:45.285 --> 04:48.120
Midge, I'm serious. I have nothing .

04:48.205 --> 04:50.164
I am over, and they're
finally gonna know it.

04:50.248 --> 04:51.165
Next time you see me,

04:51.249 --> 04:52.875
there will be a bunch
of young executives

04:52.960 --> 04:54.126
picking meat off my ribs.

04:54.211 --> 04:56.295
That's a pretty picture.

04:58.882 --> 05:00.216
What's your secret?

05:02.427 --> 05:05.972
N ine different ways to say. . .

05:06.056 --> 05:09.433
"I love you , Grandma."

05:27.327 --> 05:30.079
We should get married .

05:31.540 --> 05:33.457
You think I'd make a good ex-wife?

05:33.542 --> 05:36.085
I'm serious.

05:36.169 --> 05:37.461
You have your own business.

05:37.546 --> 05:41.257
You don't mind when I come over.

05:41.341 --> 05:43.175
What size Cadillac do you take?

05:45.137 --> 05:46.220
You know the rules.

05:46.304 --> 05:47.555
I don't make plans,

05:47.639 --> 05:50.099
and I don't make breakfast.

05:54.479 --> 05:59.775
Sterling's having the tobacco people in
in nine hours, and I have nothing .

06:01.570 --> 06:03.112
People love smoking .

06:03.196 --> 06:06.240
There's nothing that you,
the Trade Commission ,

06:06.324 --> 06:09.493
orReader's Digest
can do to change that.

06:15.333 --> 06:18.127
There's this kid who comes
by my office every day,

06:18.211 --> 06:20.129
looks where he's gonna put his plants.

06:21.339 --> 06:22.465
Is he handsome?

06:43.403 --> 06:44.945
23.

06:45.030 --> 06:46.072
Uh, not right away.

06:46.156 --> 06:47.740
Pal, could you take the long way up?

06:47.824 --> 06:50.284
I am really enjoying the view here.

06:50.368 --> 06:51.494
You going to Campbell's
bachelor party?

06:51.578 --> 06:52.745
Yeah , I want to be there

06:52.871 --> 06:55.956
before they tie an anchor around his neck
and drag him out to sea.

06:56.041 --> 06:57.291
I hear she's a nice girl .

06:57.375 --> 06:58.584
Eh, who wants that?

07:04.216 --> 07:05.758
What did you do that for?

07:05.842 --> 07:07.593
She'll probably be
assigned to one of us.

07:07.677 --> 07:09.303
Then she'll know what she's in for.

07:09.387 --> 07:11.514
You got to let them know
what kind of guy you are.

07:11.598 --> 07:13.307
Then they'll know what kind of girl to be.

07:13.391 --> 07:16.310
I have a feeling we won't be going
to your bachelor party soon.

07:16.394 --> 07:19.522
Yeah , well, compared to Campbell,
I'm a Boy Scout.

07:19.606 --> 07:21.148
Excuse me. Is he expecting you?

07:21.233 --> 07:22.399
He's not expecting anything .

07:24.402 --> 07:27.321
Oh , honey, don't worry.
I'll get home safely.

07:28.573 --> 07:30.282
I have an important
appointment right now,

07:30.367 --> 07:32.326
so why don't you go
shopping or something?

07:32.410 --> 07:34.036
Take your mother to lunch .

07:34.121 --> 07:35.329
Tell her it was my idea.

07:35.413 --> 07:37.289
Wow. He's good .

07:37.374 --> 07:40.334
It's just a bachelor party, dear.

07:40.418 --> 07:43.045
No, I really don't know
what they have planned ,

07:43.171 --> 07:45.339
but judging from the creative brain power
around here,

07:45.423 --> 07:47.424
we'll probably end up
seeingMy Fair Lady.

07:49.553 --> 07:51.137
I'll tell you what.

07:51.221 --> 07:53.055
I'll drop by your place on my way home.

07:53.140 --> 07:54.431
Your mother can check
under my fingernails.

07:56.268 --> 07:58.978
Of course I love you .

07:59.062 --> 08:02.189
I'm giving up my life to be with you , aren't I?

08:05.527 --> 08:07.069
What a great gal .

08:08.446 --> 08:10.614
Tell ya, boys,

08:10.699 --> 08:12.366
she stole my heart.

08:12.450 --> 08:14.201
And her old man's loaded .

08:16.788 --> 08:18.414
Now, this is the executive floor.

08:18.498 --> 08:20.499
It should be organized , but it's not,

08:20.625 --> 08:24.962
so you'll find account executives
and creative executives all mixed in together.

08:25.046 --> 08:26.380
Please don't ask me the difference.

08:26.464 --> 08:27.381
Great.

08:27.465 --> 08:29.008
Hopefully, if you follow my lead ,

08:29.092 --> 08:31.051
you can avoid some of the mistakes
I've made here.

08:31.136 --> 08:32.761
- Hello, Joan .
- Like that one.

08:34.472 --> 08:36.390
So how many trains did it take you?

08:36.474 --> 08:38.392
Only one, but I got up very early.

08:38.476 --> 08:40.227
In a couple of years,
with the right moves,

08:40.312 --> 08:42.354
you'll be in the city with the rest of us.

08:42.439 --> 08:44.148
Of course, if you really make
the right moves,

08:44.232 --> 08:45.357
you'll be out in the country,

08:45.442 --> 08:48.194
and you won't be going to work at all.

08:48.278 --> 08:49.737
You'll be here just
across the aisle from me.

08:49.821 --> 08:52.406
We'll both take care of Mr. Draper
for the time being .

08:52.490 --> 08:55.743
I don't know what your goals are,
but don't overdo it with the perfume.

08:55.827 --> 08:57.953
Keep a fifth of something
in your desk.

08:58.038 --> 08:59.538
Mr. Draper drinks rye.

08:59.623 --> 09:02.750
Also, invest in some
aspirin , Band-Aids,

09:02.834 --> 09:04.793
and a needle and thread .

09:04.878 --> 09:05.836
Rye is Canadian, right?

09:05.921 --> 09:07.588
You better find out.

09:08.965 --> 09:10.424
He may act like he wants a secretary,

09:10.508 --> 09:11.634
but most of the time,

09:11.718 --> 09:14.553
they're looking for something
between a mother and a waitress.

09:14.638 --> 09:16.472
And the rest of the time, well . . .

09:22.062 --> 09:23.395
Go home, take a paper bag ,

09:23.480 --> 09:24.980
and cut some eyeholes out of it.

09:25.065 --> 09:26.774
Put it over your head , get undressed ,

09:26.858 --> 09:28.484
and look at yourself in the mirror.

09:28.568 --> 09:31.779
Really evaluate where your strengths
and weaknesses are,

09:31.863 --> 09:33.405
and be honest.

09:33.490 --> 09:35.449
I always try to be honest.

09:35.533 --> 09:37.326
Good for you .

09:38.536 --> 09:41.288
Now, try not to be overwhelmed
by all this technology.

09:41.373 --> 09:42.414
It looks complicated ,

09:42.499 --> 09:45.167
but the men who designed it made it
simple enough for a woman to use.

09:45.252 --> 09:46.418
I sure hope so.

09:46.503 --> 09:48.462
At lunch , pick up a box of chocolates,

09:48.546 --> 09:50.381
a dozen carnations,
and some bath salts.

09:50.465 --> 09:51.423
I'll explain later.

09:51.508 --> 09:52.883
Thank you , Miss Holloway.

09:52.968 --> 09:55.469
You're really wonderful
for looking out for me this way.

09:55.553 --> 09:57.054
It's Joan .

09:57.138 --> 09:58.931
And listen,

09:59.015 --> 10:00.641
don't take this the wrong way,

10:00.725 --> 10:03.602
but a girl like you ,
with those darling little ankles,

10:03.687 --> 10:05.562
I'd find a way to make 'em sing .

10:07.232 --> 10:09.483
Also, men love scarves.

10:09.567 --> 10:11.151
Good morning, Mr. Draper.

10:12.570 --> 10:14.738
Oh! And Mr. Sterling . How are you?

10:14.823 --> 10:15.823
Morning , girls.

10:19.244 --> 10:21.537
You look like a hundred bucks,
Long night?

10:21.621 --> 10:23.330
It's not this tobacco thing , is it?

10:23.415 --> 10:24.748
It's been on my mind .

10:24.833 --> 10:26.458
Yeah , well , I should hope so.

10:26.543 --> 10:27.501
Lee Garner, his father,

10:27.585 --> 10:29.586
the whole Lucky Strike family
will be here at 4.

10:30.839 --> 10:32.923
You worried?

10:33.008 --> 10:34.466
No.

10:34.551 --> 10:36.385
If I was worried ,
I'd ask you what you've got,

10:36.469 --> 10:39.305
but I'm not, so I'm just going to assume
you've got something ,

10:39.389 --> 10:41.390
which means you should be worried .

10:41.474 --> 10:43.851
So you came here because you wanted
to watch me get dressed?

10:43.935 --> 10:46.520
No, I wanted to make sure
you were here.

10:46.604 --> 10:50.607
In body. Give me about a half hour
for the rest of it.

10:52.610 --> 10:53.652
How do I put this?

10:53.737 --> 10:56.363
Have we ever hired any Jews?

10:56.448 --> 10:57.698
Not on my watch.

10:57.782 --> 11:00.659
That's very funny. It's not what I meant.

11:00.744 --> 11:04.079
We've got an Italian .
Salvatore, my art director.

11:04.164 --> 11:06.373
- That won't work.
- Sorry.

11:06.458 --> 11:08.542
Most of the Jewish guys
work for the Jewish firms.

11:08.626 --> 11:09.668
Yeah, I know.

11:09.753 --> 11:11.295
Selling Jewish products to Jewish people.

11:11.379 --> 11:12.546
That's very good .

11:12.630 --> 11:14.798
It's just that our 1 1 :00
is with Menken's Department Store

11:14.883 --> 11:18.177
and I wish we had someone
to make them feel. . .comfortable.

11:18.261 --> 11:20.846
You want me to run
down to the deli and grab somebody?

11:22.390 --> 11:23.599
You missed a button .

12:10.688 --> 12:13.732
Ah . Look at you , Gidget.

12:13.817 --> 12:15.401
Still trying to fill out that bikini?

12:15.485 --> 12:17.194
Summer's coming .

12:17.278 --> 12:19.488
Without the medical claims,

12:19.572 --> 12:24.618
all we have is a white box
with a red spot on it.

12:24.702 --> 12:26.161
My neighbor posed for that.

12:26.246 --> 12:29.623
Believe me, he always
looks very relaxed .

12:29.707 --> 12:31.083
Of course, he doesn't smoke.

12:31.167 --> 12:32.334
Had him hold a pencil .

12:32.419 --> 12:35.170
If I know these guys,
you're better off with a little sex appeal .

12:35.255 --> 12:37.172
Can you give me a woman
in a bathing suit,

12:37.257 --> 12:38.424
put her next to your guy?

12:38.508 --> 12:40.634
A sexy girl? I can do that.

12:40.718 --> 12:42.386
Give you a chance
to get a real model.

12:42.470 --> 12:44.638
Oh , I love my work.

12:44.722 --> 12:46.390
Speaking of sexy girls,

12:46.474 --> 12:48.267
are you going to Pete's bachelor party?

12:48.351 --> 12:49.977
I'm not really big on those things.

12:50.061 --> 12:52.604
Tell me about it. It's so embarrassing .

12:52.689 --> 12:54.189
If a girl's gonna shake it in my face,

12:54.274 --> 12:56.316
I want to be alone so I can do something .

12:57.944 --> 13:00.654
Should we drink before
the meeting or after?

13:00.738 --> 13:03.198
Or both?

13:03.283 --> 13:06.785
So. . .that's it, huh? Relax?

13:06.870 --> 13:08.620
Don't be short with me.

13:08.705 --> 13:09.997
You're the writer.

13:10.081 --> 13:12.499
I thought it was worth a try.

13:12.584 --> 13:14.293
Greta Guttman is here to see you.

13:14.377 --> 13:15.294
Send her in .

13:15.378 --> 13:16.545
Oh, great.

13:16.629 --> 13:18.755
Now we get to hear from our man in research .

13:21.885 --> 13:24.219
Mr. Draper, Mr. Romano,

13:24.304 --> 13:26.680
you both seemed more relaxed
than I expected .

13:26.764 --> 13:29.475
Do you have some kind of surprise
for the tobacco people?

13:29.559 --> 13:31.351
I'm doing my own research .

13:31.436 --> 13:33.437
If you're planning to continue
with medical testimony,

13:33.521 --> 13:36.648
you'll only be inviting
further government interference.

13:36.733 --> 13:37.816
We must police ourselves.

13:37.901 --> 13:39.693
- There's your slogan .
- The medical thing is dead .

13:39.777 --> 13:40.694
We understand that.

13:40.778 --> 13:43.030
Yes, dead . An apt choice of words,

13:43.114 --> 13:46.325
considering the public is convinced
that cigarettes are poisonous.

13:46.409 --> 13:47.743
If we can't insist that they're not,

13:47.827 --> 13:50.621
I believe my most recent surveys
have provided a solution .

13:50.705 --> 13:53.415
We can still suggest
that cigarettes are part of American life,

13:53.500 --> 13:55.125
or too good to give up,

13:55.210 --> 13:57.753
or, most appealing ,
an assertion of independence.

13:57.837 --> 14:00.172
So, basically, if you love danger,
you'll love smoking .

14:00.256 --> 14:02.716
We can put a skull
and crossbones on the label .

14:02.800 --> 14:03.717
I love it.

14:03.801 --> 14:05.469
Before the war,

14:05.553 --> 14:07.346
when I studied with Adler in Vienna,

14:07.430 --> 14:09.723
we postulated that what Freud called
the death wish

14:09.807 --> 14:10.933
is as powerful a drive

14:11.017 --> 14:13.727
as those for sexual reproduction
and physical sustenance.

14:13.811 --> 14:15.729
Freud , you say?

14:15.813 --> 14:16.730
What agency is he with?

14:16.814 --> 14:20.692
So we're supposed to believe
that people are all living one way

14:20.777 --> 14:22.736
and secretly thinking
the exact opposite?

14:22.820 --> 14:24.488
That's ridiculous.

14:24.572 --> 14:26.615
Let me tell you something,
Miss Guttman--

14:26.699 --> 14:27.866
Doctor.

14:27.951 --> 14:29.868
Dr. Guttman .

14:29.953 --> 14:32.871
Psychology might be great
at cocktail parties,

14:32.997 --> 14:37.834
but it so happens that people were
buying cigarettes before Freud was born .

14:37.919 --> 14:40.128
The issue here isn't
why should people smoke.

14:40.213 --> 14:43.298
It's why should people
smoke Lucky Strike.

14:43.383 --> 14:45.759
Suggesting that our customers have a--

14:45.843 --> 14:48.720
What did you call it? A death wish?

14:48.805 --> 14:50.681
I just don't see that on a billboard .

14:50.765 --> 14:53.517
So what if Reader's Digest
says they're dangerous

14:53.601 --> 14:55.769
They also said Bambi
was the book of the century.

14:55.853 --> 14:56.770
There's no proof.

14:56.854 --> 14:58.480
There's conclusive proof

14:58.565 --> 15:01.817
that none of these low-tar,
low-nicotine, or filtration systems

15:01.901 --> 15:04.361
have any effect on the incidences
of lung cancer.

15:04.445 --> 15:06.154
Just give me the damn report.

15:06.239 --> 15:08.532
I think you'll find it very convincing .

15:08.616 --> 15:09.783
I'm sure I will .

15:09.867 --> 15:11.076
You're the one who found

15:11.160 --> 15:13.161
all of our medical testimonials
in the first place.

15:13.246 --> 15:14.538
That's true, Mr. Draper, but I--

15:14.622 --> 15:16.039
Has anyone else seen this?

15:16.124 --> 15:17.416
Of course not. It's your account.

15:17.500 --> 15:18.875
Good .

15:20.587 --> 15:22.337
I don't want to hear about it anymore.

15:22.422 --> 15:24.881
I'm sorry, I just find your whole
approach perverse.

15:27.552 --> 15:29.553
Good luck at the meeting.

15:29.637 --> 15:31.763
I'm sure it will be a quick one.

15:37.228 --> 15:39.229
Sal , I'll take that drink now.

16:17.935 --> 16:19.895
Mr. Draper.

16:21.648 --> 16:23.857
Excuse me.

16:23.941 --> 16:25.025
Mr. Draper.

16:25.109 --> 16:28.612
I'm sorry to wake you ,
but Mr. Campbell is outside.

16:30.907 --> 16:32.407
He doesn't know I'm sleeping in here, does he?

16:32.492 --> 16:33.408
No, sir.

16:33.493 --> 16:35.702
That's good .

16:35.787 --> 16:36.703
Who are you?

16:36.788 --> 16:39.081
I'm Peggy Olsen, the new girl .

16:43.753 --> 16:47.297
Can you go out there
and entertain him?

16:48.966 --> 16:52.219
I know it's my first day,
and I don't want to seem uncooperative,

16:52.303 --> 16:54.971
but do I have to?

16:55.973 --> 16:57.307
I see your point.

16:58.309 --> 16:59.976
I brought you some aspirin.

17:04.691 --> 17:05.982
Send him in .

17:07.944 --> 17:09.528
You look like a hundred bucks.

17:09.612 --> 17:11.488
Ready to go sweet-talk
some retail Jews?

17:11.572 --> 17:14.116
You are tough to take
first thing in the morning , Pete.

17:14.200 --> 17:15.701
I've never had any complaints.

17:15.785 --> 17:17.744
Speaking of which,
who's your little friend here?

17:17.829 --> 17:19.538
She's the new girl .

17:19.622 --> 17:21.456
You always get the new girl .

17:21.541 --> 17:23.250
Management gets all the perks.

17:24.252 --> 17:25.585
Where are you from , honey?

17:25.670 --> 17:27.921
Miss Deaver's Secretarial School.

17:28.005 --> 17:29.339
Top notch .

17:29.424 --> 17:30.716
But I meant where are you from?

17:30.800 --> 17:33.927
Are you Amish or something?

17:34.011 --> 17:36.930
No. I'm from Brooklyn .

17:37.014 --> 17:38.056
Well, you're in the city now.

17:38.141 --> 17:40.142
It wouldn't be a sin
for us to see your legs.

